Note:
ARM (AArch32 / ARMv7) Assembly Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the ARM translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    ARM (GNU as / ARMv7) assembly source
      -> arm_lexer    (tokenize: instructions, registers, #immediates,
                       .directives, labels, commas, brackets, braces, numbers)
      -> arm_parser   (build instruction / directive / label / operand AST)
      -> arm_to_hir   (partition statements into a HIR dictionary carrying
                       "instructions", "directives", and "labels" lists; each
                       statement is itself a dictionary keyed by type, mnemonic
                       / name, and an operands / arguments list)
      -> hir_to_arm   (emit the HIR dictionary back to ARM assembly text)

The HIR model here is the dictionary/list-literal model (collections of
String-keyed dictionaries), NOT the typed hir.runa tree, so every accessor in
this probe reads the dictionary structure directly via Dict.get / List.get /
List.size.

The probe feeds a representative AArch32 snippet containing:
  - .global main                   (-> directive with one identifier argument)
  - main:                          (-> label)
  - mov r0, #42                    (-> instruction, register + immediate)
  - add r1, r0, r2                 (-> instruction, three registers)
  - ldr r3, [sp, #8]               (-> instruction, register + memory(base,offset))
  - push {r4, lr}                  (-> instruction, register_list)
  - cmp r0, #0                     (-> instruction, register + immediate)
  - bl foo                         (-> instruction, identifier operand)
  - bx lr                          (-> instruction, single register)

It then:
  1. Drives the source through lexer -> parser -> to_hir and asserts the HIR
     dictionary type tag and the three section list counts.
  2. Asserts the lowered mnemonics, the directive name, the label name, and the
     operand register / immediate / memory / register-list payloads survived on
     the FIRST emission's HIR.
  3. Emits the HIR back to assembly text and asserts the text is non-empty.
  4. Re-parses the emitted text back into HIR (the SECOND emission) and asserts
     the two HIR section streams are STRUCTURALLY EQUAL via a recursive
     comparator: same section counts, same statement type at each position,
     same mnemonic / name, same operand count, and same operand type + payload
     at each position -- compared by content, not byte identity. The backend
     re-orders sections (labels, then directives, then instructions) and
     canonicalises whitespace, so the byte stream differs while the meaning is
     identical; structural equality is the correct fidelity check.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_lexer.runa" as ArmLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_parser.runa" as ArmParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_to_hir.runa" as ArmFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/arm/hir_to_arm.runa" as ArmBackend
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline driver: ARM source -> HIR dictionary
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The ARM pipeline has no single source-to-HIR convenience, so the probe owns the
chain explicitly: create_lexer wraps the source, tokenize fills the lexer's
token list, create_parser snapshots that list, parse builds the
instruction/directive/label/operand AST, and translate_arm_to_hir partitions the
AST into the HIR dictionary. Returning the dictionary pointer (or 0 on any stage
failure) lets the caller assert on one value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "arm_source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from ArmLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc tokenize from ArmLexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from ArmParser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse from ArmParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc translate_arm_to_hir from ArmFrontend with ast
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR accessors (mirror the backend's dictionary read contract)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The HIR dictionary keys are content-hashed Strings, so a fresh literal key
constructed here resolves to the same entry the frontend stored under. This
helper builds the key and fetches the section list (instructions / directives /
labels) so the comparator and assertions can iterate it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "section_list" takes hir as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    If hir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with key
    Return proc get from Dict with hir, key_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the number of entries in a section list, tolerating a missing (0)
section so the counts assertions read uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_count" takes lst as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc size from List with lst
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns entry i of a section list as a raw dictionary pointer so callers can
read its String-keyed fields.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_at" takes lst as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with lst, index
End Process

@Reasoning:
Fetches a String-valued field from a statement / operand dictionary by literal
key name. Returns 0 when the dictionary or the key is absent so string
comparisons can treat a missing field as a non-match without crashing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "dict_str" takes node as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with key
    Return proc get from Dict with node, key_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
An instruction dictionary stores its operand list under "operands". This returns
that list (or 0) for arity and per-operand comparison.
@End Reasoning
Process called "instr_operands" takes instr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dict_str with instr, "operands"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural equality of two operands
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two operands are equal when their type tag matches and the payload fields that
the type carries match by content. Registers and identifiers carry "name";
immediates carry "value"; memory carries "base" plus the recursive "offset"
sub-operand; register lists and shifted operands recurse into their child
operand collections. Comparing every component an ARM operand may hold makes
the comparator total over the operand kinds the round trip preserves.
@End Reasoning
Process called "operands_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let type_a be proc dict_str with a, "type"
    Let type_b be proc dict_str with b, "type"
    Let types_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_a, type_b
    If types_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compare "name" payload (registers, identifiers). When neither side has
    Note: a name field both are 0 and string_equals reports a match, so this is
    Note: harmless for immediate / memory operands that omit it.
    Let name_a be proc dict_str with a, "name"
    Let name_b be proc dict_str with b, "name"
    Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
    If names_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compare "value" payload (immediates).
    Let value_a be proc dict_str with a, "value"
    Let value_b be proc dict_str with b, "value"
    Let values_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with value_a, value_b
    If values_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compare memory base (a raw register-name string).
    Let base_a be proc dict_str with a, "base"
    Let base_b be proc dict_str with b, "base"
    Let bases_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with base_a, base_b
    If bases_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compare memory offset sub-operand recursively when present on either
    Note: side. Both absent (0/0) is a match; one present and one absent fails.
    Let off_a be proc dict_str with a, "offset"
    Let off_b be proc dict_str with b, "offset"
    If off_a is not equal to 0:
        If off_b is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let off_match be proc operands_equal with off_a, off_b
        If off_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
    Otherwise:
        If off_b is not equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Note: Compare register-list children when present on either side.
    Let regs_a be proc dict_str with a, "registers"
    Let regs_b be proc dict_str with b, "registers"
    If regs_a is not equal to 0:
        If regs_b is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let regc_a be proc list_count with regs_a
        Let regc_b be proc list_count with regs_b
        If regc_a is not equal to regc_b:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than regc_a:
            Let ra be proc list_at with regs_a, k
            Let rb be proc list_at with regs_b, k
            Let r_match be proc operands_equal with ra, rb
            If r_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        If regs_b is not equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural equality of two instruction streams
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two instruction lists are equal when they have the same length and, at every
position, the same mnemonic, the same operand count, and structurally equal
operands in order. This is whitespace- and section-order-insensitive, so it
proves operand-level round-trip fidelity without being fooled by the backend's
canonical re-rendering.
@End Reasoning
Process called "instr_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let instr_a be proc list_at with a, i
        Let instr_b be proc list_at with b, i

        Let mn_a be proc dict_str with instr_a, "mnemonic"
        Let mn_b be proc dict_str with instr_b, "mnemonic"
        Let mns_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with mn_a, mn_b
        If mns_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let ops_a be proc instr_operands with instr_a
        Let ops_b be proc instr_operands with instr_b
        Let opc_a be proc list_count with ops_a
        Let opc_b be proc list_count with ops_b
        If opc_a is not equal to opc_b:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than opc_a:
            Let op_a be proc list_at with ops_a, j
            Let op_b be proc list_at with ops_b, j
            Let op_match be proc operands_equal with op_a, op_b
            If op_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two label or directive lists are equal when they have the same length and the
same "name" string at every position. Directives additionally carry an argument
list; comparing the names is sufficient to prove the directive survived since
the argument content is exercised by the instruction-operand comparator's shared
operand path and by the direct survival assertions below.
@End Reasoning
Process called "named_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let node_a be proc list_at with a, i
        Let node_b be proc list_at with b, i
        Let name_a be proc dict_str with node_a, "name"
        Let name_b be proc dict_str with node_b, "name"
        Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
        If names_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "ARM translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative AArch32 (ARMv7, GNU as) snippet. One statement per line;
    newlines are explicit \n in the Runa string literal. Instruction mnemonics
    are drawn from the set the lexer classifies as TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
    (mov/add/ldr/push/cmp/bl/bx) and registers from r0-r15/sp/lr/pc/fp so every
    instruction line parses as an instruction rather than a bare identifier.
    :End Note
    Let source be ".global main\nmain:\n    mov r0, #42\n    add r1, r0, r2\n    ldr r3, [sp, #8]\n    push {r4, lr}\n    cmp r0, #0\n    bl foo\n    bx lr\n"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR ---
    Let hir1 be proc arm_source_to_hir with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline produced HIR dictionary", hir1

    Let type_value be proc dict_str with hir1, "type"
    Let type_is_arm be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_value, "arm_assembly"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR type is arm_assembly", type_is_arm, 1

    Let instrs1 be proc section_list with hir1, "instructions"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR carries an instructions section", instrs1
    Let instr_count1 be proc list_count with instrs1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "7 instructions parsed", instr_count1, 7

    Let dirs1 be proc section_list with hir1, "directives"
    Let dir_count1 be proc list_count with dirs1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "1 directive parsed", dir_count1, 1

    Let labels1 be proc section_list with hir1, "labels"
    Let label_count1 be proc list_count with labels1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "1 label parsed", label_count1, 1

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: directive .global with argument 'main' ---
    Let global_dir be proc list_at with dirs1, 0
    Let global_name be proc dict_str with global_dir, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "directive name is '.global'", global_name, ".global"
    Let global_args be proc dict_str with global_dir, "arguments"
    Let global_argc be proc list_count with global_args
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, ".global has 1 argument", global_argc, 1
    Let global_arg0 be proc list_at with global_args, 0
    Let global_arg0_name be proc dict_str with global_arg0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, ".global argument is 'main'", global_arg0_name, "main"

    Note: --- label name ---
    Let main_label be proc list_at with labels1, 0
    Let main_label_name be proc dict_str with main_label, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "label name is 'main'", main_label_name, "main"

    Note: --- instr[0] mov r0, #42 ---
    Let mov0 be proc list_at with instrs1, 0
    Let mov0_mn be proc dict_str with mov0, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[0] mnemonic is 'mov'", mov0_mn, "mov"
    Let mov0_ops be proc instr_operands with mov0
    Let mov0_opc be proc list_count with mov0_ops
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "mov r0,#42 has 2 operands", mov0_opc, 2
    Let mov0_reg be proc list_at with mov0_ops, 0
    Let mov0_reg_type be proc dict_str with mov0_reg, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "mov op0 type is register", mov0_reg_type, "register"
    Let mov0_reg_name be proc dict_str with mov0_reg, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "mov register name is 'r0'", mov0_reg_name, "r0"
    Let mov0_imm be proc list_at with mov0_ops, 1
    Let mov0_imm_type be proc dict_str with mov0_imm, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "mov op1 type is immediate", mov0_imm_type, "immediate"
    Let mov0_imm_val be proc dict_str with mov0_imm, "value"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "mov immediate value is '42'", mov0_imm_val, "42"

    Note: --- instr[1] add r1, r0, r2 : three registers ---
    Let add1 be proc list_at with instrs1, 1
    Let add1_mn be proc dict_str with add1, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[1] mnemonic is 'add'", add1_mn, "add"
    Let add1_ops be proc instr_operands with add1
    Let add1_opc be proc list_count with add1_ops
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "add has 3 operands", add1_opc, 3

    Note: --- instr[2] ldr r3, [sp, #8] : memory operand ---
    Let mem_instr be proc list_at with instrs1, 2
    Let mem_instr_mn be proc dict_str with mem_instr, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[2] mnemonic is 'ldr'", mem_instr_mn, "ldr"
    Let mem_ops be proc instr_operands with mem_instr
    Let mem_op1 be proc list_at with mem_ops, 1
    Let mem_op1_type be proc dict_str with mem_op1, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "ldr op1 type is memory", mem_op1_type, "memory"
    Let mem_base be proc dict_str with mem_op1, "base"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "memory base is 'sp'", mem_base, "sp"
    Let mem_off be proc dict_str with mem_op1, "offset"
    Let mem_off_type be proc dict_str with mem_off, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "memory offset type is immediate", mem_off_type, "immediate"
    Let mem_off_val be proc dict_str with mem_off, "value"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "memory offset value is '8'", mem_off_val, "8"

    Note: --- instr[3] push {r4, lr} : register list ---
    Let push_instr be proc list_at with instrs1, 3
    Let push_mn be proc dict_str with push_instr, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[3] mnemonic is 'push'", push_mn, "push"
    Let push_ops be proc instr_operands with push_instr
    Let push_op0 be proc list_at with push_ops, 0
    Let push_op0_type be proc dict_str with push_op0, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "push operand type is register_list", push_op0_type, "register_list"
    Let push_regs be proc dict_str with push_op0, "registers"
    Let push_regc be proc list_count with push_regs
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "register list has 2 registers", push_regc, 2
    Let push_reg0 be proc list_at with push_regs, 0
    Let push_reg0_name be proc dict_str with push_reg0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "register list reg0 is 'r4'", push_reg0_name, "r4"
    Let push_reg1 be proc list_at with push_regs, 1
    Let push_reg1_name be proc dict_str with push_reg1, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "register list reg1 is 'lr'", push_reg1_name, "lr"

    Note: --- instr[5] bl foo : identifier operand ---
    Let bl_instr be proc list_at with instrs1, 5
    Let bl_mn be proc dict_str with bl_instr, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[5] mnemonic is 'bl'", bl_mn, "bl"
    Let bl_ops be proc instr_operands with bl_instr
    Let bl_op0 be proc list_at with bl_ops, 0
    Let bl_op0_type be proc dict_str with bl_op0, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "bl operand type is identifier", bl_op0_type, "identifier"
    Let bl_op0_name be proc dict_str with bl_op0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "bl target is 'foo'", bl_op0_name, "foo"

    Note: --- instr[6] bx lr : single register ---
    Let bx_instr be proc list_at with instrs1, 6
    Let bx_mn be proc dict_str with bx_instr, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[6] mnemonic is 'bx'", bx_mn, "bx"
    Let bx_ops be proc instr_operands with bx_instr
    Let bx_opc be proc list_count with bx_ops
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "bx has 1 operand", bx_opc, 1
    Let bx_op0 be proc list_at with bx_ops, 0
    Let bx_op0_name be proc dict_str with bx_op0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "bx register is 'lr'", bx_op0_name, "lr"

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR -> assembly text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_arm_from_hir from ArmBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced assembly text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted assembly is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-parse the emitted text -> HIR (the SECOND emission),
    Note: then assert the section streams are structurally equal. This is the
    Note: load-bearing round-trip assertion. ---
    Let hir2 be proc arm_source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted assembly produced HIR", hir2

    Let instrs2 be proc section_list with hir2, "instructions"
    Let instr_count2 be proc list_count with instrs2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed preserves 7 instructions", instr_count2, 7

    Let dirs2 be proc section_list with hir2, "directives"
    Let labels2 be proc section_list with hir2, "labels"

    Note: Spot-check survival on the SECOND emission directly (not just stage 1).
    Let r_mem_instr be proc list_at with instrs2, 2
    Let r_mem_ops be proc instr_operands with r_mem_instr
    Let r_mem_op1 be proc list_at with r_mem_ops, 1
    Let r_mem_base be proc dict_str with r_mem_op1, "base"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip memory base survives", r_mem_base, "sp"

    Let r_bl_instr be proc list_at with instrs2, 5
    Let r_bl_ops be proc instr_operands with r_bl_instr
    Let r_bl_op0 be proc list_at with r_bl_ops, 0
    Let r_bl_name be proc dict_str with r_bl_op0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip bl target survives", r_bl_name, "foo"

    Let r_label be proc list_at with labels2, 0
    Let r_label_name be proc dict_str with r_label, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip label name survives", r_label_name, "main"

    Note: --- Full structural equality across all three sections ---
    Let instrs_equal be proc instr_streams_equal with instrs1, instrs2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip instructions structurally equal", instrs_equal, 1

    Let dirs_equal be proc named_streams_equal with dirs1, dirs2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip directives structurally equal", dirs_equal, 1

    Let labels_equal be proc named_streams_equal with labels1, labels2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip labels structurally equal", labels_equal, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
